<sn><md>### Isomorphous Substitution

Dominant in **2:1 clays**, minor in **1:1 clays**.<br>
It occurs when one structural cation is replaced by another of ++similar size++ but **different valence**, producing a `permanent charge`.

Example (octahedral sheet):

* Replacing Al³⁺ with Mg²⁺ → one excess negative charge<br>
  This negative charge is balanced by adsorbed cations (Na⁺, K⁺, etc.).

Example (tetrahedral sheet):

* Replacing Si⁴⁺ with Al³⁺ → one excess negative charge

Charge illustrations:

* Al³⁺–OH → Mg²⁺–OH (one excess negative charge)
* Si⁴⁺–O → Al³⁺–O (one excess negative charge)

Not all substitutions produce negative charges.
If a **lower-charge cation is replaced by a higher-charge cation**, a **positive charge** develops.

Example:

* Mg₃(OH)₆ → Mg₂Al(OH)₆⁺ <br>
  (One Al³⁺ replaces Mg²⁺ → excess positive charge, common in Fe/Al oxides in tropical soils)</md></sn><sn><md>### Factors Affecting Isomorphous Substitution{.text-center}

#### Size of the Ions

Substitution occurs when ionic radii are similar.
Examples:

* Na⁺ (0.098 nm) ↔ Ca²⁺ (0.099 nm)
* Mg²⁺ (0.066 nm) ↔ Fe³⁺ (0.064 nm)
* Al³⁺ (0.051 nm) can replace Si⁴⁺ (0.042 nm) or Mg²⁺/Fe³⁺ due to intermediate size
* K⁺ (0.133 nm) is too large to replace Na⁺ or Ca²⁺

####  Valence of the Ions

Valence difference should not exceed **one unit**.
Example:

* Na⁺ can replace Ca²⁺ despite valence difference of one.<br>
  Both ionic size and valence together determine substitution ability.

#### Type of Clay Mineral

* Very significant in **2:1 clays** (montmorillonite, vermiculite, illite)
* Sheets are loosely held and allow substitution
* Resulting charges are **permanent and not pH-dependent**
</md></sn><sn><md>### Isoelectric Point (Zero Point of Charge)

Soil colloids can carry **positive or negative charges** depending on pH.

* Negative charges → cation exchange
* Positive charges → anion exchange

H⁺ and OH⁻ are **potential-determining ions**.
The **isoelectric point (pH₀)** is the pH where **total surface charge becomes zero**.

Example:

* Gibbsite: isoelectric point = **pH 7.0**

  * pH &gt; 7 → negatively charged
  * pH &lt; 7 → positively charged
